Let $\mathbb{F}$ be the set of all functions from $\mathbb{Z}^+ \to \mathbb{Z}^+$. Consider a function $p(n)$ which represents the number of female pastors in Lutheran churches in Africa at year $n$. Also consider a function $g(n)$ which represents the gender justice index in Africa at year $n$. Assume $p, g \in \mathbb{F}$.

Given that $p(n)$ and $g(n)$ are both increasing functions and $g(n)$ is an even function, we are interested in studying the relationship between $g(n)$ and $p(n)$.

Consider the following two sequences:
\begin{align*}
\{a_n\} = \{p(n) - p(n-1)\}_{n=2}^{\infty} \\
\{b_n\} = \{g(n) - g(n-2)\}_{n=3}^{\infty}
\end{align*}

Assume that both $\{a_n\}$ and $\{b_n\}$ are bounded sequences.

1. Prove or disprove: If $\lim_{n \to \infty} a_n = \lim_{n \to \infty} b_n = L$, then $p(n)$ and $g(n)$ must have the same order of growth as $n \to \infty$.
2. Prove or disprove: If $\lim_{n \to \infty} a_n = L_1$ and $\lim_{n \to \infty} b_n = L_2$ with $L_1 \neq L_2$, then $p(n)$ and $g(n)$ cannot have the same order of growth as $n \to \infty$.
